So you have to pay for your loans, and pay for your rent  or for whatever. That period of time in which some of your costs you can not get rid of. You have to pay them. We call that time, **the short-run**.
In the short-run your decision is essentially is not whether your going to exit the industry and get rid of your fixed costs.

Your decision is basically are you going to open the doors or are going to close, I'm going to hire am I going to use variable cost or no.

If the revenue per unit, which is a price, is more that the variable cost per unit, which is the average variable cost. Then it make sense to keep open because some revenue on every unit is done and that revenue can be applied  to the fixed costs.

In the short run, if the *price* you charge **is less than** the *average variable cost*, then you should **shut down**, don't open anything, stay closed.

But in the short term you should probably **open** if the *price* is **higher than** your *average variable cost*. 

That's much different than the long run decision when you have actually no fixed costs and you can do pretty much anything you want.
